included.summary:
I am a User Experience Researcher at Fidelity Investments. My key strengths include experimental design, user research design, contextual inquiries, UI design, production scheduling, biometrics, and agile design. I have led and created usability studies for various multi-million-dollar AAA gaming studios along with leading Lenovo.com website usability studies. I work directly with stakeholders, project managers, designers, and executives throughout the user experience design process. I am well diverse in quantitative and qualitative research methods. I am capable of project management, self-motivation, and work well by myself or with a team.
If you have any questions for me please contact me at copenich@gmail.com or here on Linkedin.com.

Thank you for visiting and I hope to hear from you soon.
included.headline: User Experience Researcher

included.description:
Led numerous usability studies for a AAA 4X NDA strategy title. Created experimental
designs for each study along with generating multiple hypotheses. Incorporated biometrics into each usability study in the form
of eye tracking. Recruited participants for each usability study based on specific demographic criteria via Google Surveys. Gathered quantitative data using Fluid Surveys and qualitative data via video recordings, and post interviews. Usability reports included data such as top findings, NPS, expert recommendations, UI recommendations, and executive summaries. Managed a team of four or more people at a time during each usability study and submitted reports on schedule.
included.title: AAA Undisclosed video game usability studies

included.description: Ran user research studies on several websites for a client. Exercised survey creation using Fluid Surveys. Recruited participants for testing via Google Surveys and quantified all data collected using Microsoft Excel. Used Tobii Eye Tracking glasses and Tobii Analysis software to generate heat maps and gaze plots for UI recommendation.
included.title: UI Experimental Website Usability Studies
